title: NASA Delays Crewed Lunar Landing Until 2027 As Trump Prepares For Office
description: The United States is pushing back its planned return to the Moon from 2026 to "mid-2027" as it deals with heat shield issues and other troubles plaguing its Orion crew capsule, NASA officials said Thursday.

title: Kamala Harris again slammed for 'fake accent' as she makes first public appearance after Howard University speech
description: Kamala Harris reappeared at the National Black Caucus of State Legislators conference after the presidential election. Social media users criticized her for using a "fake accent," similar to accusations during her campaign. Some users also commented on her appearance, suggesting she appeared intoxicated, echoing previous online remarks.
author: TOI World Desk

title: Pakistanis can now enter Bangladesh without security clearance
description: Bangladesh's interim government has waived the security clearance requirement for Pakistani visa applicants, signaling a potential thaw in bilateral relations. This move follows the recent allowance of direct cargo shipments from Karachi to Chittagong, further suggesting improving ties between the two nations after a period of tension.

title: Namibia elects its first female president in disputed elections
description: Vice-president Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah avoids runoff vote, as win extends Swapo party’s 34-year hold on powerNamibia has elected its first female leader, with Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah declared the winner of last week’s presidential election in a result that will extend the ruling Swapo party’s 34-year hold on power.Nandi-Ndaitwah, the current vice-president, won with 57% of the vote, according to official results, defying predictions that she might be forced into a runoff. Swapo has ruled the country since its independence from apartheid South Africa in 1990. Continue reading...
author: Rachel Savage and agencies in Windhoek

title: Joe Biden addresses America’s ‘original sin’ of slavery on Angola visit
description: US president remembers ‘stolen men and women and children brought to our shores’ and lauds American investment in countryJoe Biden addressed America’s history of enslavement in a speech on Tuesday at Angola’s National Museum of Slavery, calling it “our nation’s original sin” during a trip in which he also lauded recent US investment in the region.“We remember the stolen men and women and children who were brought to our shores in chains, subjected to unimaginable cruelty,” Biden said, as the sun set over the water behind him.
